{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"fd316f1d-2a83-4116-91ce-da4f29f29d6d","content":"Here's the evaluation performance analysis for `EvalHeavy.csproj`:\n\n## Issues Found\n\n### 1. File I/O Property Function (High Impact)\n```xml\n<BuildNotes>$([System.IO.File]::ReadAllText('build-notes.txt'))</BuildNotes>\n```\nReading files via property functions executes during **evaluation** (not build execution), blocking the project load. This is expensive and runs on every evaluation — including IDE load, restore, and design-time builds.\n\n**Fix:** Move file reading to a target with `Inputs/Outputs` so it only runs during execution when needed.\n\n### 2. Overly Broad Glob (Medium Impact)\n```xml\n<AdditionalFiles Include=\"**\\*.*\" Exclude=\"**\\bin\\**;**\\obj\\**\" />\n```\nThis walks the **entire directory tree** during evaluation. If the project sits near large directories (e.g., `node_modules`, `.git`, packages), this becomes very expensive. It also defeats incremental evaluation caching since any new file invalidates the glob.\n\n**Fix:** Use `DefaultItemExcludes` to exclude known large directories, or narrow the glob to specific extensions/paths.\n\n### 3. Deep Import Chain (Low-Medium Impact)\n```\nEvalHeavy.csproj → level1.props → level2.props → level3.props\n```\nA 3-level chain here is modest, but this pattern can become expensive as it grows. Each import adds evaluation overhead with additional file existence checks and XML parsing.\n\n**Fix:** Flatten imports where possible, or consolidate into a single `.props` file.\n\n---\n\n**Summary:** The biggest wins are removing the `File::ReadAllText` call from evaluation and narrowing the `**\\*.*` glob.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"a227fcb2-f148-4299-9936-6215ad139ebf","outputTokens":409,"requestId":"7C17:149BD4:C0343B:DC177A:6A027FC1"},"id":"6abadb03-d4da-4560-98de-118a959d22fd","timestamp":"2026-05-12T01:18:04.492Z","parentId":"9d7a4939-e6ec-4f0b-a94a-6d6461f7bf96"}
